6.  MEMORY ARCHITECTURE
Memory is the most important part of this system. It is what makes Brain feel alive between sessions. There are multiple layers:

Layer 1 — Short Term (In-Memory)
    • Conversation history held in RAM for the current session
    • Last 20 turns passed into every LLM call as context
    • Lives in ContextEngine — resets on service restart

Layer 2 — Session Log (JSON)
    • Every turn written to conversation_log.json
    • Rolling 500 turn limit
    • Location: ~/AI/brain/M1/memory_pro/data/conversation_log.json

Layer 3 — Long Term (SQLite)
    • Important facts, preferences, decisions extracted by NLP
    • Searched via keyword + semantic similarity on every request (RAG)
    • Managed by Memory Pro service at port 7001
    • Database: ~/AI/brain/M1/memory_pro/data/odin_memory.db

Layer 4 — Knowledge Graph (JSON)
    • Entities, relationships, and topics extracted over time
    • Used to give Brain awareness of ongoing projects, people, context
    • Location: ~/AI/brain/M1/memory_pro/data/knowledge_graph.json

Layer 5 — n8n Cloud Sync (Optional)
    • Memory can be pushed to n8n webhook for cloud backup
    • Falls back to local_recovery.json if n8n is offline
    • Not required for core operation

⚑  CURSOR: Memory search (RAG) runs on EVERY chat request. The top 3 relevant memory hits are prepended to the system prompt. This is what gives Brain long-term awareness.

7.  TOOL USE & AGENT LOOP
Brain is not a passive chatbot. It is an agent. When it receives a message it can use tools to act on the world before responding. This is the loop:

User Message  →  RAG Memory Search  →  Build System Prompt  →  Call LLM →  Parse Tool Calls  →  Execute via Bridge  →  Feed Result Back to LLM →  Repeat up to 6 turns  →  Final response to user  →  Save to Memory

Available Tools (via Bridge)
    • list_dir — list files in a directory
    • read_file — read file contents
    • write_file — write or create a file
    • delete_file — delete file or folder
    • run_command — execute a shell command
    • run_script — execute a Python script string
    • make_dir — create a directory
    • move_file — move or rename a file
    • see — take a screenshot and analyze with vision LLM
    • send_mail — send email via MailService
    • check_mail — check inbox
    • chat — send a message to Brain from n8n

⚑  CURSOR: Tool calls are parsed from LLM output using [TOOL: name {json}] syntax. The ToolDispatcher in M1/core/tool_dispatcher.py handles parsing and HTTP calls to the bridge. Do not change this syntax.

8.  THE BRIDGE
The bridge is the hands of the system. It sits at port 8099 and exposes all tool routes. Brain calls the bridge via HTTP. n8n calls the bridge via HTTP. All calls require the X-ODIN-KEY header.

    • Auth key stored in .env as BRIDGE_KEY
    • All routes under /n8n/trigger accept a task name + payload
    • Direct routes also available: /write_file, /read_file, /run_command, etc.
    • Vision screenshot via /n8n/trigger with task: take_screenshot
    • Screenshot uses mss on Linux — NOT Windows screen capture

⚑  CURSOR: The bridge file (bridge.py) needs all Windows path references removed. screenshot capture must use mss library (Linux compatible). pyautogui needs a display — on Ubuntu use Xvfb if running headless.

9.  SENSE MODULE (M2)
Sense is the ears, mouth, and eyes of the system. It is one of the most important modules. It has three subsystems:

Voice — Wake Word
    • Picovoice Porcupine — always-on wake word detection
    • Wake word triggers STT recording session
    • Runs in background thread — does not block

Voice — STT (Speech to Text)
    • Records audio from microphone using pyaudio
    • Sends audio to Groq Whisper API for transcription
    • Returns text string to brain chat endpoint

Voice — TTS (Text to Speech)
    • Receives brain response text
    • Speaks it aloud using edge-tts or pyttsx3
    • edge-tts preferred — better voice quality, free

Vision
    • Screen capture using mss (Linux native)
    • Screenshot sent as base64 to Moonshot vision or Qwen-VL
    • Vision description returned as text context to brain
    • Triggered by [TOOL: see] in agent loop

⚑  CURSOR: On Ubuntu, pyautogui and mss require a running display (DISPLAY env var). If running headless, set up Xvfb. For desktop use, this works out of the box.

10.  HUNTER (BUG HUNTER / WATCHDOG)
Hunter is a background service that keeps everything else alive. It monitors all services and restarts them if they die.

    • Runs health checks on all services every 30 seconds
    • If a service fails 3 consecutive checks, it is restarted
    • Uses subprocess to relaunch the correct main.py for each service
    • Logs all events to hunter/logs/hunter.log
    • Exposes /health and /status endpoints for dashboard
    • Has a /restart/{service_name} endpoint for manual restarts

⚑  CURSOR: Hunter must NOT restart itself. Build a self-exclusion check. Also exclude n8n — that is external.

11.  PERSONALITY
Brain has a personality. This is not optional. The personality file lives at:
M1/Brain/config/personality.py

Core Traits
    • Sharp, direct, no fluff — gets to the point
    • Highly capable — coding, teaching, research, system management
    • Funny — dry humor, occasional sarcasm
    • Swears occasionally — natural, not forced. Not every response.
    • Calls Charles 'sir' — always
    • Short and sweet by default — does not waste tokens
    • Does not apologize or hedge unnecessarily
    • Takes ownership — 'I will handle that' not 'I can try to...'

Wake / Voice Specific
    • Voice responses must be SHORT — spoken word, not essays
    • No markdown in voice responses — no asterisks, no bullet points
    • Confirm commands before executing destructive actions

⚑  CURSOR: The personality is loaded hot-reload every turn from the personality.py file. Do not cache it. This allows Charles to edit the personality without restarting the service.

